Children are considered uninsured if they did not have private health insurance, Medicare, Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), a State-sponsored health plan, other government programs, or military health plan (includes TRICARE, VA, and CHAMP-VA) at the time of interview.

Title: Percentage of being uninsured at the time of interview for children under age 18 years (95% confidence intervals), United States
Description: Based on the question, "Is [child's name] covered by any kind of health insurance or some other kind of health care plan?" and a series of questions that seek to determine the health insurance coverage type for the child. Children are considered uninsured if they did not have private health insurance, Medicare, Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), a State-sponsored health plan, other government programs, or military health plan (includes TRICARE, VA, and CHAMP-VA) at the time of interview.

Children aged < 6 months are excluded from this estimate.

Children aged < 6 months are excluded from this estimate.

Description: Based on the question, "Is [child's name] covered by any kind of health insurance or some other kind of health care plan?" and a series of questions that seek to determine the health insurance coverage type for the child. Children are considered uninsured if they did not have private health insurance, Medicare, Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), a State-sponsored health plan, other government programs, or military health plan (includes TRICARE, VA, and CHAMP-VA) at the time of interview.

Description: Based on the question, "Is [child's name] covered by any kind of health insurance or some other kind of health care plan?" and a series of questions that seek to determine the health insurance coverage type for the child. Title: Percentage of being uninsured at the time of interview for children under age 18 years (95% confidence intervals), United States
Description: Based on the question, "Is [child's name] covered by any kind of health insurance or some other kind of health care plan?" and a series of questions that seek to determine the health insurance coverage type for the child. Children are considered uninsured if they did not have private health insurance, Medicare, Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), a State-sponsored health plan, other government programs, or military health plan (includes TRICARE, VA, and CHAMP-VA) at the time of interview.

Children are considered uninsured if they did not have private health insurance, Medicare, Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), a State-sponsored health plan, other government programs, or military health plan (includes TRICARE, VA, and CHAMP-VA) at the time of interview.
